english:
  title: A Farewell Ode for Yi Sisa, Departing to Govern Namwon
  author: Yi Sung-in
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Gain and loss, profit and harm—they come without fixed time. The gentleman accepts them with ease, as one dons a fur robe in winter's cold or linen in summer's heat, responding only to what meets him. He has never shown even a hair's breadth of contrivance in this. Thus the ancients said: "When the Way declines, it is Heaven's decree." And again: "That I have not met with opportunity is Heaven's doing." How were the ancients able to be thus? Simply because gain and loss, profit and harm belong to the world outside, not to oneself. What we call the self remains still and profound within. When we treat what lies outside as though it stirs our inner being, we are deluded. We need only perfect what lies within ourselves.

    Yi of Wansan is truly a man of principle. Though he served the court for ten years, his talents had not yet found full expression. In the autumn of the year Sinhai, when the realm purged the treacherous and renewed its governance, the Prince commanded his ministers, saying: "Let those in office be worthy. The censor is my eyes and ears—upon this depends much. Choose with utmost care." The minister, accepting this charge with reverence and caution, put forward Yi Yi, the Minor Keeper of the Secret Archives, and the Prince appointed him Inspector of the Censorate with the rank of Abiding Constancy.

    On that very day, Yi donned his court robes and appeared at court, his sash arranged and tablet held straight, his bearing dignified and composed. All who saw him, whether acquainted or not, exclaimed in unison: "The realm has gained a capable man, and Yi has found his moment. The sovereign does not bestow office lightly, nor does the subject receive it without merit." They fully expected great accomplishments from him.

    Yet within mere months, he was sent out to govern Namwon, a minor prefecture. Many were puzzled. An inspector of the Censorate sent to such a place? Yesterday the realm elevated Yi, today it seems to diminish him. Even I harbored doubt. But when I visited him, I found his countenance serene and his speech mild—not a trace of grievance appeared. So this is one who accepts his lot with ease and yet fulfills his duty without complaint.

    Consider Yi's record: he first entered the censorate and became a renowned inspector; later he governed Rimju and proved himself a worthy magistrate; afterward, as a circuit inspector, he benefited an entire province. His abilities are boundless, his resourcefulness inexhaustible. With such talents applied to governing Namwon, he shall move through it as freely as a master craftsman's blade through yielding space. The world has long forgotten the praise of virtuous magistrates. Should the future speak of a southern governor who simplified administration, lightened the people's burden, and allowed them to dwell contentedly in their homes and prosper in their callings—surely that must be Yi.

    So I both celebrate his noble bearing and encourage him toward great accomplishments, for such is the unfailing bond between friends.
  footnotes:
    - Wansan (完山) is an ancient name for the Jeonju region, Yi's native place, used here as an honorific reference.
    - The 'year Sinhai' likely refers to 1431 CE, marking a significant purge and administrative reorganization in early Joseon Korea.
    - The imagery of the blade moving without resistance (from Zhuangzi) suggests perfect, effortless mastery in governance.
    - Yi Yi served as an inspector of the Censorate (司憲侍史), a prestigious but scrutinizing position, before his appointment as magistrate of Namwon.
